Inflation in Europe is on the rise due to food
The accelerating inflation in the euro area is mainly due to the constant increase in food prices.
The November price increase in 13 eurozone countries was higher than expected, after 2.6 per cent annual inflation was recorded at 3.1 per cent in October, the Luxembourg Statistical Office of the Union said.
The official forecast was only 3%, Bloomberg reported.
Unlike the U.S., UK and Canadian issuing banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not lowered the basic interest rate, with the reduction, along with rising commodity prices and falling unemployment, leading to an inflationary spiral.
The ECB would like to keep the inflation rate below 2%, but close to them.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in an absurd situation: it must “remove” inflation so that it does not have to do anything about it later.
In Germany, November’s inflation represents a 3.3 per cent 15-year record; in Spain it rose from 3.6 per cent to 4.1 per cent.
Inflation in the euro area has erupted due to sharply rising food and energy prices.
Term wheat prices have risen by 88 percent, and soybean prices have reached their highest since 1973.
In 2007, it was also necessary to pay significantly more for edible oil and dairy products.
The price of oil in the world markets this year rose by 52 percent and last month already cost one barrel of black gold almost $100.
According to the ECB, inflation will jump from 2.1 per cent this year to 2.5 per cent in 2008, but it will already fall to 1.9 per cent in 2009.
According to analysts, the level of 12-month inflation in the next 3-4 months will remain at about 3%, but its average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to immediately reduce interest rates twice during 2008.
