In many places, it is saved on disinfectants
This year, more than a thousand cases of infection have been registered in hospitals, mainly due to inappropriate use of antibiotics.
The hygienic conditions of the hospitals, the overcrowding of the beds, the overload of the staff to stop the disease do not help, says the primary of the National Epidemiological Center.
In many places, it is also saved on disinfectants.
Recently, MRSA infection was diagnosed at the traumatological department of St. John's Hospital.
Bacteria resistant to antibiotics have been discovered in a man who got to the hospital after a serious traffic accident.
The patient was isolated.
A similar infection occurred at the same site at the beginning of the year.
The patient injured in a serious car accident was released home, but soon after he had to return with an MRSA infection and due to the bacteria in his body, one important operation could not be performed yet.
By December 10, 1,094 hospital infections caused by multi-resistent pathogens had been reported to the National Nesocomialis Surveillance System, said Karolina Böröczov<0xC3><0xA1>, mayor of the National Epidemiological Center.
This means that so many infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens have been recorded in hospitals with certainty, others are not known.
Nearly two-thirds (683) of infections were caused by MRSA, or methicillin-oxacilin resistant gold staphylococcus.
Bacteria Staphylococcus aureus (SA) carry a third of people in the nose without causing the disease.
Infections caused by SA (e.g. throat inflammation, tonsillitis, skin infections, early infections) respond well to antibiotics and can be treated well.
However, if antibiotics are administered excessively or inappropriately, bacteria that react well to antibiotics develop into bacteria that are very resistant to antibiotics and that are rapidly spreading under inadequate hospital conditions.
Especially in the case of temporary or permanent malfunctioning of the immune system in patients with a weakened body, low body weight or in patients in years can cause serious hospital infections, such as acute infection or blood poisoning - sepsis.
According to the top doctor of St. John's Hospital, there is nothing special about MRSA infection, a similar infection is a daily practice in hospitals.
"Infection should not be confused with epidemics, MRSA is not only there," said Tibor Nyulasi, "where the presence of the cause of the disease is not investigated."
Resistant to antibiotics
"We are isolating these patients, treating them in rubber gloves and in a mask, and we have the antibiotics we need to treat them," said Tibor Nyulasi.
Patients admitted to the hospital are first tested for the presence of MRSA in their body, however, infection cannot always be avoided.
Sampling is not fashionable
The vast majority of hospital infections caused by MRSA could be prevented, but the current conditions and conditions in home hospitals are not conducive to the prevention of the emergence and spread of multi-resistant pathogens, says Karolina Böröczov<0xC3><0xA1>.
Since this infection occurs symptomatically in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should monitor admitted patients and isolate MRSA carriers immediately.
However, sampling of microbiological samples in Hungarian hospitals is not in fashion.
It also plays a role in the fact that the National Health Insurance Fund does not finance this examination.
Most cases are detected if the patient suffers from a noticeable MRSA infection, said the primary epidemiological center.
The European Union has strict recommendations for the appropriate treatment of antibiotics in the field of human medicine and there are also domestic directives for the treatment of individual infections, epidemiologists.
It is necessary to strive for antibiotic therapy to be targeted, i.e. microbiological examinations should be carried out to prevent the development of drug resistance, but even hospitals do not comply with this in all cases.
Drawings of microbiological samples are even rarer in basic and outpatient treatment of patients, Karolina Böröczov<0xC3><0xA1> said.
Save on disinfectants
According to scientific evidence, MRSA is most often spread among patients through health care personnel.
Therefore, hand washing and the use of gloves and masks play a very important role, but even in hospitals there are serious deficiencies.
MRSA is transmitted by capillary infection and touch, but it is not always possible to isolate infected patients under the conditions of home hospitals.
On the contrary, the rooms are often crowded, the beds are often very close to each other, although from an epidemiological point of view, patients should be at least 1.5 meters away from each other.
As Karolina Böröczov<0xC3><0xA1> noted, unfortunately, we can also meet with the fact that in hospitals that are in an adverse material situation, they save on disinfectants, there are few nurses and many patients, so there is a chance of infection again.
According to Karolina Böröczov, where the necessary protective measures are followed, similar infections are demonstrably less or the further spread of the cause of the disease can be stopped.
Government Programme against MRSA
Treatment of MRSA infection is a huge expense for health insurance companies, which is why it is being fought everywhere.
For example, in England, the government has written a program to prevent MRSA and reduce its incidence.
As it appears, the program is successful, according to published data, MRSA infections in England show a decreasing trend.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) ranks prevention of multi-resistent pathogens (including MRSA), and hospital infections caused by these pathogens, among its priorities.
