The U.S. Federal Reserve, the European Central Bank and the central banks of Britain, Switzerland and Canada have decided to jointly fight the financial market crisis.
This means that more than $100 billion will be delivered to the currency markets through auctions.
In these auctions, banks charge an interest rate at which they are willing to borrow money.
For example, the U.S. Fed will send $40 billion to auction, and then another $40 billion will be made available to European and Swiss central banks.
It is the first time since the attacks of September 11 that the central banks of individual states have agreed on a coordinated procedure to prevent or mitigate the consequences of the financial crisis.
“This move is aimed at addressing the biggest problems of the economy, the growing lack of free capital that banks could borrow,” wrote Bernard Baumohl of the Economic Outlook Group in a report to clients.
“Coordinated actions by the central banks have reduced the likelihood of a recession in the United States from 65 percent to 50 percent,” Baumohl said in the report.
Banks have already lost $60 billion due to unpaid loans, especially in the United States.
Analysts expect billions more losses.
“Central banks need to be really afraid of what else might follow when they decide to do this,” said ABN chief economist Amro Kieran Davies.
"It looks like the situation is really bad," he added.
Central banks are concerned that if banks themselves have difficult access to loans, they will be more likely to lend to their customers.
This would reduce consumption and put the U.S. economy in a recession with potential impacts on global economic growth.
The central banks thus decided after failing to reduce the so-called LIBOR rate, the London interbank rate, which is used to lend money on the interbank market.
This meant that banks were still concerned about borrowing money from each other, despite the fact that the central banks of the United States, Canada and the United Kingdom lowered their interest rates several times during the fall.
“It will have the same effect as another interest rate drop,” Greg Salvaggio of Tempus Consulting told Reuters.
Some analysts do not think that a move by the central banks will contribute to settling the crisis because it does not solve the underlying problem, and that is the collapse of the US real estate market.
