Compulsive memory
After more than sixty years in a confidential regime, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which depict the fate of the 17.5 million victims of Hitler’s regime, are opening to the public.
The 47 million archival documents stored for 27 km in Bad Arolsen (Hesse) were accessible to date only for "humanitarian" purposes, that is, individually and specifically, at the request of the former victim or his authorized persons.
Eleven states responsible for managing the archives - including Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May to open them to scientists and historians.
Since the process of ratification of this agreement by all States is at an end, yesterday’s opening took effect.
Sensitive Information
The free access of historians to Bad Arolsen will allow to explore "particularly the movements of prisoners, the population of camps and the health of forced workers", explains Reto Meistern, director of these archives managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (Comité international de la Croix-rouge).
Until recently, several states, including Germany, were opposed to making these naming documents available to the public, due to the sensitive nature of some information.
What are the alleged homosexuality or mental disabilities of some victims of deportation?
After the war, the registers of concentration camps or detainees compiled by the Gestapo were collected for the practical purpose of finding deported or forced labor of civilians subjected to them, bringing them proof of their internment in order to open the way for their compensation.
Today, more than 300 permanent employees in Bad Arolsen are still dealing with tens of thousands of individual applications.
However, for part of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen is only a limited benefit.
"We cannot expect anything fundamentally new from these documents," said Prof. Wolfgang Benz, director of the Center for the Study of Anti-Semitism at the Technische Universität Berlin in 2006.
