Congress approves MiFID transposition effective November 1st
At the same time as the parliamentary hearings, which ended today with a Congressional vote on the amendments incorporated by the Senate into the bill, the government submitted to a public hearing of regulations developing the new law, with the aim of both coming into force before the end of the year.
Representatives of the parties have consistently highlighted the efforts of MPs and senators to negotiate and agree on the best standard to ensure the protection of investors and the detailed regulation of the activities of entities necessary for the effective functioning of the markets.
The MiFID Directive, which regulates the Securities Trading Act, provides for the modernization of financial markets and at the same time strengthens investor protection, improves the supervisory powers of the State Securities Markets Commission (CNMV) and promotes cooperation between European institutions.
This new regulation will enable financial advisory services to be provided to both specialised firms and natural or legal persons and will create a new type of financial service provider (ESSI), financial advisory firms (AFI), which connect to the companies with securities and securities brokers.
In addition, the number of systems for performing transactions with financial instruments is being expanded by joining regulated secondary markets through multilateral trading systems and order internalisation systems that will compete with current exchange brokers.
The law further obliges investment services companies to disseminate information on key aspects of their business profile, exposure to risk and ways of dealing with risk in the market, and requires a report of all operations performed to simplify supervision by CNMV.
During the discussion in the Congressional Trade Commission, a number of amendments were included, among which stands out that securitised receivables are considered to be a "complex" financial instrument due to the high risk posed to the investor by the risks that have been shown to be high by the US.
In addition, the transposition of the directive was used to legalize functions that may be held by bachelors in economics and business management 30 years after the Royal Decree was approved in 1977, which outlines professional functions reserved for economists.
At the same time, the Senate has ordered the creation of new professions in the financial sector, such as an intermediary that will work externally, will not require permission from CNMV and will be able to provide product trading and customer acquisition services for different investment firms at the same time.
