Concerns over new gas dispute between Russia and Ukraine
Russia and Ukraine are currently in a dispute over the prices of natural gas, thus increasing the risk that Russian supplies of this fuel to Western Europe may be affected.
Most of the Russian fuel exported to the European Union (EU) is piped through Ukraine and any dispute between the two countries is closely monitored.
Kyiv warned that if Moscow raises gas prices to Ukraine, Russia will be charged higher transit fees.
The previous dispute between the two countries last year reduced deliveries to EU countries.
The latest dispute between Kiev and Moscow comes at a time when the Ukrainian government and the Russian state-owned gas monopoly, Gazprom, are trying to agree on how much Ukraine will have to pay for Russian gas in 2008.
Gazprom says it will have to charge more to Ukraine, as it has agreed to pay up to 50% more for the gas it receives from neighboring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say this could mean that Ukraine will have to pay 40% more for its supplies from Gazprom.
"It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important gas transit states during the negotiations," Ukrainian Economy Minister Anatoly Kinach told Reuters.
"The changes in gas prices should undoubtedly be linked to our arguments regarding the amount of transit fees (to Western Europe) through Ukraine," he said.
The last major dispute between Moscow and Kiev led to a reduction in supplies from Gazprom to Ukraine in January 2006.
This caused a sharp drop in exports to Western Europe, which sharply raised prices.
Russian gas accounts for a quarter of all deliveries to the European Union.
Russia has the largest supply of gas in the world, but a large part of it remains underutilized.
As a result, Gazprom complements its own gas supplies from Turkmenistan and other former Central Asian Soviet republics.
The NHS “must control foreign employees”
The inspector said the Scottish chambers of the NHS must improve checks on criminal records of non-European employees.
The recommendation from the president of the supreme supervisory authority, Robert Black, came after a foreign doctor in Scotland was linked to the June attacks on Glasgow Airport.
Mr. Black also fears that the Scottish NHS has no exact idea of the amount of foreign staff it employs.
But his report emphasized that the other key checks were carried out in order on a sample of five health authorities.
The President of the Supreme Audit Office immediately after the June attacks on Glasgow Airport was interested in personnel from countries outside the European Economic Area (EEA).
Bilal Abdullah, an eighty-year-old Iraqi doctor at the Royal Alexandra Hospital in Paisley, was arrested at the airport after someone hired a Jeep to the door of the main terminal building.
He was one of three doctors who appeared in the Central Criminal Court using a video bridge accused of linking to bombing attempts in the UK.
The NHS Chambers are expected to inspect foreign personnel in terms of qualifications, experience and authorization for work in the UK prior to their employment.
Although the Scottish Health Commission uses Disclosure Scotland for criminal records checks, the agency has no authority to obtain such information outside the UK.
The president’s report says, among other recommendations, that the commission should be led by the Criminal Records Bureau, which assists employers with checks in several countries.
“Although we found that some of the staff records contained evidence of these checks, they are not carried out on a regular basis,” the report said.
Mr Black said the Scottish NHS is in many ways in line with its own pre-employment screening policy, but also added: "Our report highlights areas where the system could be improved to ensure accurate information about the amount of foreign personnel available."
BMA Scotland President Dr Peter Terry said it was “very unlikely” that pre-employment checks would identify potential NHS employees who could commit a terrorist act in the future.
"The report suggests that the current pre-employment controls at the Scottish NHS are working well and it is not clear what additional value those comments will bring," he said.
The Scottish health authorities have announced that they currently have 1,161 foreign workers, the vast majority of whom are doctors and nurses.
However, the president of the supreme control authority pointed out that these numbers will probably be higher also because the commissions had a problem identifying staff with a residence permit.
The survey also found that the NHS controls in the areas of Ayrshire and Arran, Grampian, Greater Glasgow and Clyde, Lanarkshire and Lothian are largely carried out.
They included passport checks, work permits and qualifications.
The Scottish Government is currently revising the policies and directives on pre-employment controls for NHS foreign workers.
Health Minister Nicola Sturgeon said: “I wanted to do this work immediately after the terrorist attack on Glasgow Airport.”
She also added that the Scottish government, in agreement with the health committees, is considering the recommendations of this report and will ensure that best practices are reflected in the updated pre-employment checks on all staff - including those abroad - that it plans to release next month.
