The climate on Venus may be a prospect for the future of the Earth
Scientists announced yesterday that Venus may have once been a pleasant place to live.
Data from a European orbiting station show that the planet is even more similar to the Earth's twin head than previously thought.
Venus is Earth's closest planetary neighbor.
These two worlds are about the same size and orbit along similar paths, but Venus is a little closer to the Sun.
Scientists now believe that billions of years ago, conditions on Venus were similar to those on Earth and could have been habitable.
But the depleted greenhouse effect caused by carbon dioxide, the atmospheric erosion of solar radiation and the lower speed of rotation sent Venus on a completely different path of development.
Today, the planet is waterless, the surface temperature is hot enough to melt lead, and it is devastated by storms and hurricane-force winds.
The findings from the European Space Agency’s Venus Express probe, which studied the planet for a year, offer a poor view of how Earth could evolve in the event of catastrophic climate change.
Professor Fred Taylor from the Department of Physics at the University of Oxford and one of the lead missions of Venus Express said: “It is becoming clearer why the climate on Venus is so different from that on Earth, even though the planets themselves are quite similar.
"Our new data allows us to compose a scenario in which Venus began as well as Earth, perhaps even with the habitable environment, billions of years ago."
