Does the subprime mortgage crisis affect the American credit card market?
When there is blood in the water, naturally, the spinal cords begin to flush excitedly around.
Now that the U.S. real estate market is booming, predators have focused on the credit card market there.
Analysts at Goldman Sachs say credit card losses could reach $99 billion if subordinated mortgages infect other variants of consumer loans.
The signs of tension are clear.
Increasing number of insolvency cases (with more than 30-day payment delays) and debited accounts (accounts that the provider deems unenforceable).
HSBC Bank announced last month that it had lost $1.4 billion in the U.S. consumer credit market - also due to insolvent credit card loans.
However, it is too early to panic.
Deprecated accounts and inability to pay are still few.
According to Moody’s, the third-quarter insolvency rate was 3.89% below average by almost a whole percentage point.
The deteriorating rates can be explained in part by technical reasons.
The change in the U.S. Personal Bankruptcy Act of 2005 led to a sharp decline in the number of reported bankruptcies, which make up a large part of the losses on credit cards; therefore, the number of reports (and thus the number of debits) would increase regardless of whether the general conditions for defaults were met.
The sector also shows a good maturity rate, which shows how many consumers pay monthly off their debts.
And confidence in the securities of secured credit cards is solid, despite the paralysis in other corners of structured finance.
Dennis Moroney of TowerGroup predicts that their emissions in 2007 will be 25% higher than last year.
There are definitely direct ways to spread the infection between the subprime mortgage crisis and the credit card market: when property loans dry up in real estate, consumers are more likely to be indebted through credit cards.
Credit card issuers, however, are more likely to look at cash flow than at the values of the deposits, so falling home prices may not necessarily mean a change in the creditworthiness of lenders.
They may even be beneficial to lenders.
Consumers’ motivation to repay mortgages decreases when the value of their assets falls below the value of the loan; as a result, the debt on the cards moves up on the list of priorities to repay.
Card issuers will also be able to respond more quickly and flexibly to more stormy conditions than mortgage providers by changing interest rates or debt limits.
This should theoretically reduce the risks of a rapid change in the price of pledged items.
“It’s not going to happen that one beautiful morning we’ll just reevaluate all the loans,” said Gary Perlin, chief financial officer at Capital One.
Although the risk of a sub-mortgage-style explosion is low, the risk of gradual weakening is far more real.
If lower home prices and debt reductions push America into a recession, the credit card industry will face a darker future.
